<DocsLayout title="Getting Started" description="Get started with lean-ctx in under 5 minutes.">
  <p>
    lean-ctx is an MCP (Model Context Protocol) server that sits between your AI coding tool and
    the LLM. It caches file reads, compresses CLI output, and extracts signatures to reduce token
    consumption by 89-99%.
  </p>

  <h2>Prerequisites</h2>
  <ul>
    <li>Node.js 20 or higher</li>
    <li>An MCP-compatible editor: Cursor, GitHub Copilot, Claude Code, or Windsurf</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>How It Works</h2>
  <p>
    lean-ctx registers 5 MCP tools that your editor can call instead of (or in addition to)
    its built-in file read, shell, and search tools. Each tool applies domain-specific optimizations:
  </p>

  <table>
    <thead>
      <tr>
        <th>Tool</th>
        <th>Replaces</th>
        <th>Savings</th>
      </tr>
    </thead>
    <tbody>
      <tr>
        <td><code>ctx_read</code></td>
        <td>File reads (Read tool)</td>
        <td>89-99%</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td><code>ctx_tree</code></td>
        <td>Directory listings (ls, find, Glob)</td>
        <td>~40%</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td><code>ctx_shell</code></td>
        <td>Shell commands (Shell tool)</td>
        <td>60-90%</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td><code>ctx_benchmark</code></td>
        <td>—</td>
        <td>Measurement tool</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td><code>ctx_metrics</code></td>
        <td>—</td>
        <td>Session statistics</td>
      </tr>
    </tbody>
  </table>

  <h2>Quick Install</h2>

  <pre><code>git clone https://gitlab.pounce.ch/root/lean-ctx
cd lean-ctx
npm install
npm run build</code></pre>

  <p>
    After building, you need to configure your editor to use the lean-ctx MCP server.
    See the <a href="/docs/installation">Installation guide</a> for editor-specific instructions.
  </p>

  <h2>Verify It Works</h2>
  <p>
    Once configured, restart your editor and look for lean-ctx in the MCP tools list.
    You should see 5 tools: <code>ctx_read</code>, <code>ctx_tree</code>, <code>ctx_shell</code>,
    <code>ctx_benchmark</code>, and <code>ctx_metrics</code>.
  </p>

  <p>
    Run <code>ctx_benchmark</code> on any file in your project to see the exact token savings
    for each compression strategy.
  </p>

